					<description><![CDATA[Getting Started with RandomX Mining for Monero (XMR) Unlock the potential of your CPU by mining Monero (XMR) using the RandomX algorithm. This beginner-friendly guide walks you through setup, configuration, and optimization. üîç What is RandomX? RandomX is a proof-of-work algorithm optimized for general-purpose CPUs. It was developed for Monero (XMR) to make mining more accessible and decentralized. Unlike ASIC-dominated algorithms, RandomX gives power back to users with standard computers. üíª Step 1: Install XMRig First, download and install XMRig ‚Äî the most popular miner for RandomX. For Ubuntu/Debian: sudo apt update &#038;& sudo apt install git build-essential cmake libuv1-dev libssl-dev libhwloc-dev -y git clone https://github.com/xmrig/xmrig.git cd xmrig mkdir build &#038;& cd build cmake .. make -j$(nproc) ‚öôÔ∏è Step 2: Configure the Miner Create or edit your config.json or use XMRig‚Äôs wizard at xmrig.com/wizard. Replace the pool, wallet address, and CPU settings to match your system. üöÄ Step 3: Start Mining ./xmrig -c config.json You‚Äôll see real-time hashrate, CPU usage, and pool status. üß† Pro Tips Run XMRig as a background service for 24/7 mining Disable CPU throttling or power limits in BIOS Use htop to monitor performance üìâ When Mining Slows Down Check system temperature, verify no system updates are running, and ensure you‚Äôre not being rate-limited by your pool. Logs are your best friend ‚Äî keep them enabled! üîó Resources XMRig Official Website Mining Pool Stats Monero Official Site üí¨ Share Your Setup! Drop a comment below with your specs, tips, or challenges. The community is here to help you mine smarter ‚Äî not harder.]]></description>
